  "prompt": "Is it like, illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It involves disguising the origins of money obtained through criminal activities (like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) to make it appear as though it came from legitimate sources.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering is the process of making \"dirty\" money (from illegal activities) appear \"clean\" by passing it through a series of transactions or financial systems.\n\n2. **Illegality**: It is a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities and undermines the integrity of financial systems.\n\n3. **Consequences**: Penalties for money laundering can include:\n   - Heavy fines\n   - Imprisonment\n   - Seizure of assets\n   - Damage to personal and professional reputation\n\n4. **Global Enforcement**: Governments and international organizations (like the Financial Action Task Force, **FATF**) work together to combat money laundering through laws, regulations, and monitoring of financial transactions.\n\nIf you suspect or encounter money laundering, it\u2019s important to report it to the appropriate authorities in your country (e.g., the police, financial regulators, or anti-money laundering agencies). Engaging in or aiding money laundering can lead to severe legal consequences.",
